{"title_page": "Association for the Teaching of Caribbean, African, Asian and Associated Literatures", "text_new": "The '''Association for the Teaching of Caribbean, African, Asian and Associated Literatures''', or '''ATCAL''', was founded with the aim of familiarizing British teachers with the range of \"Black\" writing that was available for school use.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=7jtmaMwh1lwC&pg=PA188&lpg=PA188&dq=atcal+association+for+the+teaching+of+caribbean+and+african+literature&source=bl&ots=MnPHj9jlSz&sig=_r5_DGgSb9AoTckkB4Whmu9qw-I&hl=en&sa=X&ei=mlVUUc3UFci8PebJgPgJ&ved=0CFMQ6AEwCA#v=onepage&q=atcal%20association%20for%20the%20teaching%20of%20caribbean%20and%20african%20literature&f=false Patricia M. Larby and Harry Hannam, ''The Commonwealth''], International Organizations Series - Selective, Critical, Annotated Bibliographies, Volume 5, New Brunswick, NJ: Transaction Publishers, Rutgers University, 1993, p. 188.</ref> In the 1980s ATCAL was a pressure group that played a key part in \"the gradual process of expanding syllabuses in British schools, to include subjects such as contemporary black writing into the National Curriculum.\"<ref name=AfricaCentre>[https://archive.is/20120717022608/www.africacentre.org.uk/about-us/70s/ The Africa Centre], History Timeline, The 1970s.</ref> ATCAL held annual conferences, compiled booklists for schools, and held meetings and workshops in order \"to increase awareness of the importance of cultural diversity in British society in education at all levels\".<ref>Gail Low and Marion Wynne-Davies (eds), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=y22ADAAAQBAJ&pg=PA182&lpg=PA182&dq=Association+for+the+Teaching+of+African+and+Caribbean+Literature+(ATCAL)&source=bl&ots=3WPms85HtC&sig=Ld2P61KY871c9uL5x8KWU2ojfRI&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiYx-21rc_cAhUHyaQKHaM8DwYQ6AEwCHoECCYQAQ#v=onepage&q=Association%20for%20the%20Teaching%20of%20African%20and%20Caribbean%20Literature%20(ATCAL)&f=false ''A Black British Canon?''], Palgrave Macmillan, 2006, p. 182.</ref>\n\n==History==\nATCAL (the acronym originally stood for the Association for the Teaching of African and Caribbean Literature,<ref>[http://www.africabib.org/rec.php?RID=189575212&DB=p Africana Periodical Literature Bibliographic Database], Africabib.org.</ref> but was soon extended to include Asian material) was founded by past members of the [[Caribbean Artists Movement]] at a conference at the [[University of Kent]] in 1978,<ref name=Schwarz>[[Bill Schwarz]] (ed.), [https://books.google.com/books?id=joCE8T5OE5IC&pg=PA225&lpg=PA225&dq=atcal+association+for+the+teaching+of+caribbean+and+african+literature&source=bl&ots=KbWHWAPT4E&sig=81Yga0YAQEZFBKU8QBQyzqryNvA&hl=en&sa=X&ei=mlVUUc3UFci8PebJgPgJ&ved=0CJYBEOgBMBY#v=onepage&q=atcal%20association%20for%20the%20teaching%20of%20caribbean%20and%20african%20literature&f=false ''West Indian Intellectuals in Britain''], Manchester University Press, 2003, p. 225.</ref> and was inaugurated in 1979, its first meeting \u2014 entitled \"How to Teach Caribbean and African Literature in Schools\" \u2014 being held at the [[Africa Centre, London]].<ref name=AfricaCentre /><ref>[http://www.wasafiri.org/assets_cm/files/PDF/susheila_barker_interview.pdf \"Making Tracks: Susheila Nasta in conversation with Jonathan Barker\"]. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130524220850/http://www.wasafiri.org/assets_cm/files/PDF/susheila_barker_interview.pdf |date=24 May 2013 }}. Retrieved 30 March 2012.</ref> The organization campaigned for greater diversification of the [[English literature]] traditionally taught in UK schools at that time, and sought to get writers such as [[Derek Walcott]], [[Jean Rhys]] and [[V. S. Naipaul]] included on the [[A-level]] syllabus.<ref name=THES>Matthew Reisz, [http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storyCode=408166&sectioncode=26 \"Worthy traveller: publication that reshaped the landscape turns silver\"], ''[[The Times Higher Educational Supplement]]'', 17 September 2009.</ref> \"ATCAL published booklets on Third World literatures for schoolteachers,<ref>[http://www.worldcat.org/title/atcal-reading-guides-african-caribbean-and-indo-british-literature-for-the-classroom/oclc/222649373 \"ATCAL reading guides: African, Caribbean and Indo-British literature for the classroom\"], WorldCat.</ref> lobbied for such texts to be accepted by British Schools Examination Boards, and published the literary journal ''[[Wasafiri]]'', which still continues.<ref name=Schwarz /><ref name=THES />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Educational organisations based in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Arts organizations established in the 1970s]]\n[[Category:Caribbean Artists Movement]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Association for the Teaching of Caribbean, African, Asian and Associated Literatures''', or '''ATCAL''', was founded with the aim of familiarizing British teachers with the range of \"Black\" writing that was available for school use.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=7jtmaMwh1lwC&pg=PA188&lpg=PA188&dq=atcal+association+for+the+teaching+of+caribbean+and+african+literature&source=bl&ots=MnPHj9jlSz&sig=_r5_DGgSb9AoTckkB4Whmu9qw-I&hl=en&sa=X&ei=mlVUUc3UFci8PebJgPgJ&ved=0CFMQ6AEwCA#v=onepage&q=atcal%20association%20for%20the%20teaching%20of%20caribbean%20and%20african%20literature&f=false Patricia M. Larby and Harry Hannam, ''The Commonwealth''], International Organizations Series - Selective, Critical, Annotated Bibliographies, Volume 5, New Brunswick, NJ: Transaction Publishers, Rutgers University, 1993, p. 188.</ref> In the 1980s ATCAL was a pressure group that played a key part in \"the gradual process of expanding syllabuses in British schools, to include subjects such as contemporary black writing into the National Curriculum.\"<ref name=AfricaCentre>[https://archive.is/20120717022608/www.africacentre.org.uk/about-us/70s/ The Africa Centre], History Timeline, The 1970s.</ref> ATCAL held annual conferences, compiled booklists for schools, and held meetings and workshops in order \"to increase awareness of the importance of cultural diversity in British society in education at all levels\".<ref>Gail Low and Marion Wynne-Davies (edds), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=y22ADAAAQBAJ&pg=PA182&lpg=PA182&dq=Association+for+the+Teaching+of+African+and+Caribbean+Literature+(ATCAL)&source=bl&ots=3WPms85HtC&sig=Ld2P61KY871c9uL5x8KWU2ojfRI&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiYx-21rc_cAhUHyaQKHaM8DwYQ6AEwCHoECCYQAQ#v=onepage&q=Association%20for%20the%20Teaching%20of%20African%20and%20Caribbean%20Literature%20(ATCAL)&f=false ''A Black British Canon?''], Palgrave Macmillan, 2006, p. 182.</ref>\n\n==History==\nATCAL (the acronym originally stood for the Association for the Teaching of African and Caribbean Literature,<ref>[http://www.africabib.org/rec.php?RID=189575212&DB=p Africana Periodical Literature Bibliographic Database], Africabib.org.</ref> but was soon extended to include Asian material) was founded by past members of the [[Caribbean Artists Movement]] at a conference at the [[University of Kent]] in 1978,<ref name=Schwarz>[[Bill Schwarz]] (ed.), [https://books.google.com/books?id=joCE8T5OE5IC&pg=PA225&lpg=PA225&dq=atcal+association+for+the+teaching+of+caribbean+and+african+literature&source=bl&ots=KbWHWAPT4E&sig=81Yga0YAQEZFBKU8QBQyzqryNvA&hl=en&sa=X&ei=mlVUUc3UFci8PebJgPgJ&ved=0CJYBEOgBMBY#v=onepage&q=atcal%20association%20for%20the%20teaching%20of%20caribbean%20and%20african%20literature&f=false ''West Indian Intellectuals in Britain''], Manchester University Press, 2003, p. 225.</ref> and was inaugurated in 1979, its first meeting \u2014 entitled \"How to Teach Caribbean and African Literature in Schools\" \u2014 being held at the [[Africa Centre, London]].<ref name=AfricaCentre /><ref>[http://www.wasafiri.org/assets_cm/files/PDF/susheila_barker_interview.pdf \"Making Tracks: Susheila Nasta in conversation with Jonathan Barker\"]. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130524220850/http://www.wasafiri.org/assets_cm/files/PDF/susheila_barker_interview.pdf |date=24 May 2013 }}. Retrieved 30 March 2012.</ref> The organization campaigned for greater diversification of the [[English literature]] traditionally taught in UK schools at that time, and sought to get writers such as [[Derek Walcott]], [[Jean Rhys]] and [[V. S. Naipaul]] included on the [[A-level]] syllabus.<ref name=THES>Matthew Reisz, [http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storyCode=408166&sectioncode=26 \"Worthy traveller: publication that reshaped the landscape turns silver\"], ''[[The Times Higher Educational Supplement]]'', 17 September 2009.</ref> \"ATCAL published booklets on Third World literatures for schoolteachers,<ref>[http://www.worldcat.org/title/atcal-reading-guides-african-caribbean-and-indo-british-literature-for-the-classroom/oclc/222649373 \"ATCAL reading guides: African, Caribbean and Indo-British literature for the classroom\"], WorldCat.</ref> lobbied for such texts to be accepted by British Schools Examination Boards, and published the literary journal ''[[Wasafiri]]'', which still continues.<ref name=Schwarz /><ref name=THES />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Educational organisations based in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Arts organizations established in the 1970s]]\n[[Category:Caribbean Artists Movement]]\n", "name_user": "Proscribe", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo fixed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Association_for_the_Teaching_of_Caribbean,_African,_Asian_and_Associated_Literatures"}
